The prerequisite clement of a direct and irreconcilable antagonism between the two eminent teachers of Tacitus is therefore wholly and significantly wanting, and hence there existed no motive for including Secundus in the ² criminatio,' with which Maternus and Messalla 011 the one side, and Aper, their equally fervent opponent, on the other, good-naturedly threaten one another in parting. Summing up the previous discussion, we conclude that, after Messalla had finished, Secundus followed in a speech, and that he in turn was succeeded by Maternus, who brings the entire debate to a close. But the beginning and end of Secundus' speech, the end of Messalla's, and the beginning of that of Maternus are lost in the two lacunae (c. 35 ext. 40 7) which unfortunately disfigure . the closing portions of the treatise.
